snippet.textDisplay:
My Ruth Doctor Theory

The doctor is the timeless child (in the visions)
The master is Brendan or the Doctor (makes more sense to be Brendan)
The two police officers are rassilon and omega.
They are immortal beings and the ‘timelords’ are actually future humans, rassilon does experiments to slow time around him using the power of the timeless child, which is why the clocks don’t move around the doctor (Ruth) and Brendan.
They experiment on the timeless children to extract their ability to live forever in the form of (regeneration) renewing.
The Ruth doctor is the first incarnation of the doctor and IS the timeless child in the visions.
Once she finds out what the timelords were using her for her power, she used the chameleon arch to hide her identity from the time lords to keep them from using her powers.
The timelords eventually capture Ruth and erase her memory, forcing her into a regeneration into William Hartnells doctor starting the cycle.
The master finds out that they used them, and destroys the entire planet.

‘We are not who we think, you and I’
‘Built on the lie of the timeless child’

snippet.textDisplay: One scenario could be as The Timeless Child looks a lot like a young Ruth that she is a regeneration between the 2nd and 3rd Doctors. We never saw that actual facial regeneration and the 2nd Doctor was on Gallifrey at that point. It could be the 2nd Doctor was regenerated not as an adult but as a child, maybe as part of his rehabilitation he had to make a total restart and grow up once again on Gallifrey. Later, as an adult, as final punishment, the intention was that she be exciled to Earth to help the humans, but the rehabilitation doesn't work and at some point she rebels and goes on the run once again by stealing a TARDIS. She has many adventures, but, (just like the 9th Doctor when he became a teacher) eventually has to go into hiding on Earth, buries the TARDIS, and only recovers her memory when The Time Lords send The Judoon to find her.  She is fatally injured at some point and goes into her next regeneration. Ruth's jacket looks a lot like the one John Pertwee was wearing when he first stumbled out of the TARDIS. Her Tardis is also very retro and she hadn't recognised the 13th Doctor's sonic screwdriver.  That's why The Master taunts the 13th Doctor about everything she knows being a lie, she is unaware of a whole section of her past.

snippet.textDisplay: I've always been a fan of villains in Who, but the past few years the villains haven't felt particularly "Villain-esque" but gotta say I am absolutely LOVING Ashad, this whole season kinda fixed my loss of faith of last season. The presence of the Lone Cyberman is positively menacing whenever he's got screentime... I definately can see why every trailer/interview keeps calling the Cybermen "relentless". I really hope Ashad gets defeated, but becomes the Davros figure of the cybermen, returning in future episodes to smite the Doctor - He's such a cool villain that you want to hate (ofwhich is the role of the villain). Good job Chibbs :)

0:20 Huh that's interesting.....
I wonder if Ryan's Dyspraxia will suddenly make a return and give him difficulty or if it will just be forgotten about
Considering this seems to be in line with Series 11 which had it in the first episode, one or two mentions in later episodes
Up until Resolution of the Daleks when it was brought up

Kinda insensitive for The Doctor to ask Ryan to dissect a bird in Praxeus all things considered
I really hoped that Ryan's disability/dyspraxia would have been handled better in this series than it was in Series 11
Sadly that doesn't appear to be the case....
